{
  "doc_id": "11611",
  "text": "In chronic heart failure (CHF) patients, the function of major and intermediate vessels in the systemic circulation and microvascular function are compromised (2; 3) . In recent years, the role of a failing endothelium in CHF has been recognised and investigated (4; 5). Both myocardial and peripheral perfusion are impaired, partly due to a reduction in endothelium-50 dependent vasodilatory capacity. It has been suggested that the severity of endothelial dysfunction can be used as a prognostic factor for the long term outcome in CHF and coronary artery disease (5; 6). Andreassen and colleagues [CITATION_1] found that peripheral endothelial -dependent vasodilatation is attenuated in candidates for heart transplantation, but improves within the first year after the transplantation [CITATION_2] . Also, peripheral endothelial 55 function one month after the transplantation may be used to identify the risk of cardiac allograft vasculopathy [CITATION_3] .",
